{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, the controlling figure of exile is most explicit in the opening lines, where the speaker must \"tread paths of exile\" amid his hardships on the rime-cold sea.[^1] He has decided to endure it stoically as an inexorable aspect of *wyrd* (fate), binding his grief inwardly until divine remedy or mercy appears, ultimately seeking comfort and stability from God rather than earthly consolation.[^2]\n\nIn *The Seafarer*, the figure is most explicit early on, as the speaker recounts how he \"wintered on paths of exile, bereft of kinsmen,\" suffering the ice-cold sea's miseries.[^3] He has decided to embrace it as a refining trial that redirects his soul from transient earthly joys toward the eternal \"joys of the Lord,\" which burn \"hotter\" than mortal life loaned on land.[^4]\n\nThe speakers' dispositions thus contrast: the Wanderer remains heart-weary and guarded in sorrow, resigned to transience; the Seafarer grows spiritually invigorated, with exile spurring an active longing for heaven over the world.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [p-9cca5e](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [p-5bdc65](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 5 (*The Seafarer*), [p-889339](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-889339).\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 5 (*The Seafarer*), [p-f52e2e](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-f52e2e) and [p-eff626](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-eff626).",
